  "descriptions": [
    {
      "descrType": "Overview",
      "description": "The Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II is a family of single-engine, all-weather stealth multirole combat aircraft produced in three variants: the conventional takeoff and landing F-35A, the short take-off and vertical-landing F-35B, and the carrier-based F-35C. The Joint Strike Fighter (JSF) programme aimed to replace a wide range of legacy aircraft across the US armed services and allied nations with a common, affordable, low-observable platform. More than 1,000 aircraft have been delivered to the US and partner nations.",
      "shortDescription": "Stealth multirole fighter family in three variants (A/B/C) for USAF, USMC, USN and allied nations.",
      "classification": "U"
    },
    {
      "descrType": "Design",
      "description": "The F-35 uses a blended-wing-body airframe with a single Pratt &amp; Whitney F135 turbofan. Internal weapons bays carry four AIM-120 AMRAAMs plus two AIM-9X Sidewinders in the air-to-air configuration. The AN/APG-81 AESA radar, DAS (distributed aperture system), and EOTS (electro-optical targeting system) provide sensor fusion. The F-35B variant uses a Rolls-Royce LiftSystem driven by the engine to achieve STOVL capability. All variants incorporate extensive composite construction and edge-aligned airframe shaping for low observability.",
      "shortDescription": "Single F135 turbofan with internal weapons bays, AN/APG-81 AESA radar and full sensor fusion.",
      "classification": "U"
    },
    {
      "descrType": "Usage",
      "description": "The F-35 is in service with the USAF, USMC, USN, UK, Australia, Netherlands, Norway, Italy, Japan, South Korea, Israel, Singapore, Belgium, Denmark, Finland, Poland, Switzerland and Canada. It has seen combat with Israel and the United States. The F-35A is the standard variant for land-based operations; the F-35B serves the USMC and UK aboard amphibious assault ships; the F-35C equips USN carrier air wings. The aircraft is expected to be the backbone of Western air power into the 2060s.",
      "shortDescription": "Operated by 17+ nations; in combat with Israel and the US; USAF, USMC, USN and partner-nation service.",
      "classification": "U"
    },
    {
      "descrType": "Variants",
      "description": "F-35A: conventional takeoff and landing (CTOL) for air forces. F-35B: short take-off and vertical-landing (STOVL) for marines and carriers without catapults. F-35C: carrier-based with larger folding wings and reinforced landing gear for catapult launches and arrested landings.",
      "shortDescription": "Three variants: F-35A (CTOL), F-35B (STOVL), F-35C (carrier).",
      "classification": "U"
    }
  ],
